{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 15:55:11.221176", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — enterprise OSPF network\nDate: (current snapshot)\n\nExecutive summary\n- Two user hosts (host_1_1_1_1, host_2_1_1_1) are not getting IP addresses (no DHCP lease). They have their interfaces up but no inet address; all pings from those hosts to infrastructure/services report network unreachable.\n- The FRR router plane (core/dist/server-access routers) shows healthy OSPF adjacencies and inter-router routes — the routing control plane appears up.\n- Backend web servers (20.200.0.0/24) can reach the load balancer (20.200.0.1) and peers in their subnet, and the load balancer can reach 10.200.0.0/24 services (DNS, DHCP, web frontends). However the backend hosts cannot reach hosts in 10.200.0.0/24 (DNS, DHCP, frontends) — ICMP from backend -> 10.200.0.x shows 100% loss while backend -> load_balancer is OK.\n- Application processes are running: Apache on web servers and HTTP service on load_balancer are listening on port 80.\n- Primary anomalies: (A) DHCP delivery to access hosts is failing (hosts not getting IP). (B) Traffic forwarding between backend (20.200.0.0/24) and 10.200.0.0/24 is blocked/absent for traffic originating from backend hosts even though the load balancer itself can communicate with 10.200.0.0/24.\n\nDetailed observations and evidence\n\n1) Host layer (host_1_1_1_1, host_2_1_1_1)\n- Interface state: eth0 on both hosts is UP but neither host has an IPv4 address assigned.\n  - host_1_1_1_1 ip_addr output: eth0 present but no inet line.\n  - host_2_1_1_1 ip_addr output: eth0 present but no inet line.\n- Ping attempts from the hosts to infrastructure/services show \"Network is unreachable\" (ping tool outputs). This indicates the hosts themselves are not configured with an IP and thus cannot generate or route traffic beyond their local link.\n\nImplication: DHCP is not succeeding (hosts are not getting leases). The hosts' interface up + no IP is consistent with absent DHCP OFFER/ACK or DHCP relay failures.\n\n2) DHCP server and server-side reachability\n- dhcp_server interface: eth0 configured as 10.200.0.8/24; ip route and default route present (default via 10.200.0.1).\n- dhcp_server shows some RX packets but TX packet counter in the short snapshot is low/zero (RX 11 / TX 0 in ifconfig snapshot). This suggests the server has not been sending replies in the observed window (or very little activity). It does not by itself prove a server fault, but combined with hosts having no leases indicates DHCP requests are not reaching/being processed or replies are not returning to the hosts.\n- Web servers (10.200.0.x) can reach dhcp_server and dns_server (pings from web_server_0..3 to dhcp_server/dns_server succeed). So the 10.200.0.0/24 server-access segment is routable inside the server-access side.\n\n3) OSPF / routing plane\n- router_core_1, router_core_2, router_core_3 and server_access_router show OSPF process active and routes learned. Example: OSPF entries and connected interfaces are present and show multiple areas/LSAs. server_access_router shows 10.200.0.0/24 directly connected.\n- Inter-core links and core-to-dist seem to have adjacencies (OSPF neighbors fully adjacent). Routing appears consistent and healthy from the router outputs.\n\nImplication: Control-plane (OSPF) is functioning; adjacency and route distribution are not the primary reason for hosts having no IP.\n\n4) Backend network (20.200.0.0/24) communication pattern\n- backend_web_0/1/2 addresses: 20.200.0.2–4 with default route via 20.200.0.1 (load_balancer).\n- Observed behavior from the ping matrix:\n  - backend_web_* -> load_balancer (20.200.0.1): pings succeed (0% loss).\n  - backend_web_* -> other backend peers: backend<->backend pings succeed where applicable.\n  - backend_web_* -> 10.200.0.x addresses (dns_server 10.200.0.2, dhcp_server 10.200.0.8, web frontends 10.200.0.3–6): pings fail with 100% loss.\n  - load_balancer -> dns_server: succeeds.\n  - load_balancer has addresses on both sides: eth1 = 20.200.0.1/24 and eth0 = 10.200.0.7/24.\n- netstat on load_balancer shows process listening on TCP/80 (load balancer web). Web servers and backend web servers also have HTTP listening.\n\nImplication: The load_balancer itself can reach 10.200.0.0/24 and can talk to the backend; backend hosts can reach the load_balancer. However packets originating from backend hosts toward 10.200.0.0/24 do not get through to their intended 10.200 destinations (ICMP dropped/blocked or not forwarded). Two likely categories of causes:\n  - IP forwarding disabled on the load_balancer (so it answers for its own IPs but won't route/forward packets between interfaces).\n  - A firewall or iptables/nftables rules on the load_balancer preventing traffic sourced from 20.200.0.0/24 to 10.200.0.0/24 (e.g., intentional isolation or misconfigured ACLs).\n  - Alternatively, the load_balancer may be performing NAT in one direction only (or missing SNAT) so return traffic fails — but given ICMP from backend to 10.200 is dropped at/from the 10.200 side (100% loss), the immediate drop appears before or at the load_balancer egress to 10.200 network.\n\n5) Service/process-level checks\n- netstat on web_server_0, backend_web_0 and load_balancer show HTTP services are running (TCP 0.0.0.0:80). The load balancer is listening and reachable from the server-side network.\n\nLocalization — affected components\n- Access hosts: host_1_1_1_1, host_2_1_1_1 — symptom: no IP addresses.\n- DHCP server: dhcp_server (10.200.0.8) — reachable from server network, but appears not to be sending DHCP replies to hosts (TX counters in snapshot low); likely not receiving host DHCPDISCOVER messages.\n- Distribution-layer (candidates): router_dist_1_1 (10.1.1.1 br0) and router_dist_2_1 (10.2.1.1 br0) — these are the logical location for DHCP relay (per network description). The lack of host leases suggests relay/forwarding of DHCP requests from access subnets to dhcp_server might be failing. Because hosts have no IPs, the fault is likely between hosts and DHCP server path — either in the access switch, dist router DHCP relay configuration, or an ACL blocking DHCP.\n- Load balancer: load_balancer (10.200.0.7 / 20.200.0.1) — symptomatic for asymmetric/blocked forwarding between 20.200 and 10.200 networks for traffic sourced from backend servers; it forwards/responds for itself and backends can reach it, but packets from backend to 10.200 machines are not getting through/responded to.\n\nProbable root causes (ranked by likelihood, with supporting evidence)\n1) DHCP relay or DHCP request delivery failure (high confidence)\n   - Evidence: Both hosts' interfaces are up but have no IPv4 address; ping attempts from hosts return \"Network is unreachable\". dhcp_server is reachable from web servers and server network, but hosted TX counters low in snapshot and hosts show no leases.\n   - Likely locus: distribution routers that should relay DHCP requests to the central dhcp_server (router_dist_1_1, router_dist_2_1) or the access switch path between hosts and dist routers. Either relay agent not configured/enabled, relay misconfiguration, or DHCP/BOOTP traffic (UDP 67/68) blocked by an ACL on a router or switch.\n\n2) Load balancer not forwarding/routing traffic between the backend network (20.200.0.0/24) and server-access network (10.200.0.0/24) for traffic originating from backend hosts (medium-high confidence)\n   - Evidence: backend -> load_balancer pings succeed; load_balancer -> 10.200.* succeed; but backend -> 10.200.* fail (100% loss). This pattern indicates the load_balancer is reachable from backend and can reach 10.200, but it does not forward/translate traffic from backend to that network or return traffic is dropped.\n   - Possible causes: IP forwarding disabled on load_balancer, firewall rules blocking forwarded traffic, or load_balancer configured to intentionally isolate backends from 10.200 except via application-level proxying. Given description expects the load balancer to be the only element to handle backend-to-frontend traffic, misconfiguration of forwarding/NAT/ACLs on the load_balancer is a likely root cause.\n\n3) Routing plane looks healthy; OSPF is not the root cause (high confidence)\n   - Evidence: Router OSPF outputs show adjacencies, LSA counts, and appropriate connected networks advertised. server_access_router has 10.200.0.0/24 connected and OSPF entries present across cores. The routers have correct connected interfaces; there are OSPF routes for the inter-core links.\n\nImpact summary\n- User hosts (host_1_1_1_1, host_2_1_1_1) currently have no IP configuration -> cannot reach DNS, web frontends, load balancer, or any external/infrastructure service. This effectively disconnects users from the network services.\n- Backend web servers can only reach the load_balancer and backend peers; they cannot reach DNS/DHCP/10.200.0.0 server-access hosts. Depending on application design, this may or may not be intended — but the current behavior will prevent backend hosts from resolving or contacting central infra services if needed.\n- Web frontends (10.200.0.x) and load_balancer are up and HTTP services are listening, so server-side applications appear to be running.\n\nConfidence levels\n- DHCP delivery failure to hosts: high confidence (direct evidence: hosts eth0 up but no inet, ping NX).\n- OSPF/routing control plane healthy: high confidence (OSPF outputs show adjacencies and routes).\n- Load balancer not forwarding between 20.200 and 10.200: medium-high confidence (pattern of successful local and LB-side connectivity but failed backend->10.200 connectivity).\n\nRecommended next diagnostic data to collect (investigative, not remedial)\n- On a dist router (router_dist_1_1 / router_dist_2_1):\n  - Show DHCP relay/agent configuration (if configured) or check if ip helper-address / dhcrelay is present.\n  - Capture or log for UDP 67/68 traffic on the access VLAN/br0 while a host attempts DHCP (tcpdump on the distribution interface toward the host and toward the server-access side).\n- On the access switches (switch_access_1_1_1, switch_access_2_1_1):\n  - Check VLANs and port status for host ports; confirm no ACL blocking DHCP/bootp.\n  - Verify whether DHCP broadcast from host reaches the dist router.\n- On the dhcp_server:\n  - Tail DHCP server logs while a host attempts discovery to confirm whether DISCOVER arrives and whether OFFER is generated.\n- On the load_balancer:\n  - Check sysctl net.ipv4.ip_forward and firewall (iptables/nftables) rules; capture forwarded packets (tcpdump) on both interfaces during a backend->10.200 ping to see where packets are dropped.\n  - Check load-balancer configuration for any explicit filtering between 20.200 and 10.200 networks.\n- Optionally, packet captures at three points (host access port, dist router uplink, server-access router/load_balancer) during a DHCP attempt and during backend->server ping to precisely trace whether/where traffic is dropped.\n\nConclusion\n- The control plane (OSPF) and server-side application processes are up; however, two functional anomalies prevent expected end-to-end service access:\n  1) DHCP discovery/lease process for access hosts is failing — hosts are not receiving IP addresses.\n  2) The load_balancer is not forwarding or is blocking traffic between backend (20.200) and server-access (10.200) networks for traffic originating from backend hosts.\n- Primary suspects for (1) are DHCP relay configuration or ACLs on distribution-layer devices or access switches. Primary suspects for (2) are IP forwarding or firewall/NAT rules on the load_balancer.\n\nI can run additional targeted checks (tcpdump, sysctl, or router config retrieval) on the specific devices you choose to further pinpoint the root cause(s).", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 28736, "output_tokens": 5025, "total_tokens": 33761, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 2688}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2176}}}
